Incident.Summary: Vehicle crash with fatality / Collision Reconstruction

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: September 19, 2023 The Event Data Recorder for the Honda was imaged at the Glen Burnie Barrack. The EDR analysis is attached as a PDF. The scene was mapped with a small Unmanned Aerial Vehicle. A notice to Airman was established BWI 09-137. The mapping was completed using MSP Crash 5 an Autel Evo 2. The mission was completed with one (1) flight fro eight (8) minutes. 136 color photographs were taken. The photographs were processed in the Pix4d application to produce an orthomosic image. The orthomosic image was used to create a diagram in the Map360 software. The orthomosic image was an accurate representation of the scene on September 19, 2023. Attachments: Event Data Recorder Report Diagram Pix4D Quality Report Corporal J Lantz 5563 Collision Reconstruction Specialist / sUAS Pilot State of Maryland Department of State Police CRASH Team / sUAS Team Golden Ring Office 8908 Kelso Drive Essex, Maryland 21221 James.Lantz@Maryland.Gov

Detailed Crash Investigation Report (For review by the MSPCrash Team) Section I. - Introduction: On 09/18/2023, at approximately 1317 hours, Maryland State Police Glen Burnie Barrack personnel responded to a single vehicle collision on northbound MD-295 south of I-895, Anne Arundel County, Maryland. Due to the nature of the collision, a request was made for a collision reconstructionist. I, TFC Bunger # 6459, currently assigned to the Maryland State Police Golden Ring Barrack, responded to the scene. The investigation will address the issues related to the involved operators and conditions at the time of the collision that may have caused or contributed to the collision. These issues will be addressed in this report by various investigative sources. Conclusions are based upon my investigative actions completed on scene, review of statements and interviews completed by the assigned investigator and other follow up investigative actions. My rendering of these conclusions are based upon my training and experience. Section II. - Scene Description: (The following descriptions are based on the area where the collision occurred.) Primary Roadway:Northbound MD-295 at I-895 was a three lane divided highway with a partially paved left shoulder and paved right shoulder. The lanes were separated from the left shoulder by a solid yellow line and from the paved right shoulder by a solid white line. A grass median with trees and shrubbery separated the north and southbound lanes. The posted speed limit on MD-295 was 55 mph. Environmental Conditions:The collision occurred at approximately 1317 hours. Lighting consisted of overcast daylight. Temperature was approximately 72 degrees Fahrenheit. The weather was overcast with intermittent rain in the morning, the road and median were not wet at the time of the collision. Section III. - Scene Evidence: Approximately 120 ft of pressed down grass and shrubs was observed in the center median leading to the vehicle. No furrowing was observed in the median and no tire marks were observed in the travel portion of the highway. Section IV. - Vehicle(s) Involved: Vehicle #1:2014 Honda Odyssey MD 49454CF VIN5FNRL5H67EB113988 The Honda had heavy damage to the front bumper, hood, engine, front left quarter panel, and windshield from the collision with a tree in the center median. The front left tire was off the rim. The steering column, knee bolster, and side curtain airbags had deployed. The drivers seat belt was loose and dangling from the b-pillar (the ECM revealed that the seatbelt was not engaged). Section V. - Person(s) Involved: Person #1:Gary Knollie Wileman 08/14/1988 GaryKnollie Wileman, was the operator and sole occupant of the Honda. He located unresponsive in the vehicle. EMTs resuscitated Wileman with narcan. He then went into cardiac arrest on the way to R Adams Cowley Shock Trauma. Wileman was pronounced deceased at 1334 hours. An autopsey was completed. The autopsy revealed that Wileman had abbrassions to his face and scape, a fractured pelvis, and a transection of the proximal descending thoracic aorta and left hemothorax. His cause of death was determined to be blunt force trauma and internal bleeding. Toxicology was positive for xylazine, cyclobenzaprine, fentanyl, trazadone, and desproprionyl fentanyl. Section VI. - Follow-up Investigation: 10/20/2023:Reviewed autopsy results. Section VII. - Analysis of Electronic Control Modules: Cpl Lantz # 5563, MSP CRASH Team, downloaded the electronic control module for the Honda. Two collision events were captured. The first event occurred at 78 mph and the second event occurred at 63 mph. There was no pre-imapct braking from the operator. The first event is likely the vehicle traveling off the roadway. The second event was the vehicle traveling up the embankment and then colliding with the tree. The operators seat belt was not engaged. Section VIII. - Speed Analysis: There was insufficient roadway evidence to support a speed analysis. Section IX. - Crash Dynamics: The vehicle traveled off the roadway to the left and partially up the center median embankment. It then collided with a tree at 63 mph. Section X. - Attachments that were included in for this report: The following items were attached to this report: ACRS Photos uploaded to Veripic Conclusion: The following conclusions are based upon the totality of the investigation, including the physical evidence accumulated, as well as the reports submitted by other investigators concerning this incident. Based on this evidence I have come to the following conclusions. On 09/18/2023 at approximately 1317 hours, the Honda, operated byGary Knollie Wileman, traveled off the roadway at northbound MD-295 south of I-895 into the center median. The Honda then collided with a tree at 63 mph in a posted 55 mph zone. Wileman sustained life-threatening injuries in the collision and was transported by ambulance toR Adams Cowley Shock Trauma where he was pronounced deceased at 1334 hours. Wilemanstoxicology results were positive for multiple controlled dangerous substances. The initial cause for the Honda traveling off the roadway was likely a narcotic analgesic overdose. This case is closed due to the death of at-fault party. TFC Bunger # 6459 Maryland State Police Golden Ring Barrack 8908 Kelso Dr Essex MD 21221 410-780-2700

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: Attachments: -Photograph of contraband seized, cellphone, and money -MSP form 63 -MSP form67 Victim: -Gary Knollie Wileman 8/14/1988 169 Olen Dr, Glen Burnie, Maryland 21061 Witness: -N/A Suspect: - N/A Scene Processing: -Search of victims vehicle. Narrative: -On 09/18/2023 at approximately 1430 hours, the Maryland State Police Glen Burnie barrack contacted the Maryland State Police Criminal Enforcement Division regarding a possible fatal overdose in the area northbound Maryland Route 295 north of Interstate 895. Upon arrival, investigators observed a blue 2014 Honda Odyssey bearing Maryland registration 45494CF with heavy front-end damage on the tow truck. Investigators were advised by MSP patrol units the vehicle was driven by the victim who was was involved in a single vehicle collision. The victim was positively identified by MSP Glen Burnie units as Gary Knollie Wileman. Wileman was the driver and sole occupant of the vehicle. EMS personnel observed signs of impairment and proceeded to administer Narcan to Wileman. After a few minutes, Wileman began showing signs of consciousness for a brief moment. However, Wileman was pronounced deceased by EMS personnel while enroute to Baltimore Shock Trauma. Wileman was transported to the OCME in Baltimore for an autopsy. Investigators submitted a request for the autopsy report. The Maryland State Police CRASH team was also on scene and processed the scene. Investigators followed the vehicle back to the MSP Glen Burnie barrack and conducted a search of the vehicle. Prior and after the search, the vehicle was photographed. During the search investigators located the following: -one (1) gray/gold trim iPhone located on the passenger seat. -six (6) $20-dollar bills totaling $120 located on the driver side floorboard -one (1) cut straw containing CDS residue located in the back seat MSP Glen Burnie unit contacted the next of kin and were able to return the $120. During the interview with the Wilemans next of kin, units were advised Wileman uses medication and had medical issues. In addition, Wileman was known to abuse drugs, however, the was sober for a few years. Investigators were able to conduct a consensual search of Wilemans bedroom. During the search, investigators observed ten (10) different orange pill bottles all prescribed to Wileman. In addition, there was white powdery substance was observed on Wilemans bedroom dresser. Based on the above, investigators believe this to be an overdose. Investigators will be conducting a forensic download of the cellphone. MSP Glen Burnie units will be completing the MSP form 89B and vehicle storage report. Case open. All events occurred in Anne Arundel County, Maryland.

Attachments: -Autopsy Report Victim: -Gary Knollie Wileman 8/14/1988 169 Olen Dr, Glen Burnie, Maryland 21061 Witness: -N/A Suspect: - N/A Scene Processing: -N/A Narrative: -On 10/12/2023 investigators authored a search warrant for Wilemans cellphone. The search warrant was reviewed and signed by the Honorable Judge Riley of the Anne Arundel County District Court. On 10/20/2023 investigators received the official autopsy report and toxicology report from the Medical Examiner. According to the report, the cause of death was ruled as accident, due to the motor vehicle collision. According to the toxicology report, it was discovered Wileman did have the following in his system: -fentanyl -despropionyl fentanyl -xylazine -trazodone -cyclobenzaprine The cellphone is currently at the Maryland State Police Forensic Lab awaiting forensic download. Any pertinent evidence found pertaining to CDS transactions, sell, etc. during the forensic download will be captured in a separate case number. All events occurred in Anne Arundel County, Maryland. Case closed.
